metadata.name: Kumano (Emergent Structures 1) #113
metadata.description:
"Kumano (Emergent Structures 1)" is a collection of generative works that emulate analog effects from painting, printmaking, and textile design. It is the first generative collection in a continuing series called Emergent Structures.

The title of this collection is borrowed from Kumano-zome (ÁÜäÈáéÊüì„ÇÅ), a traditional Japanese craft of resist-dyed fabric that creates beautiful analog interference patterns (moir√©). These textiles, often rendered in tones of indigo dye, date back at least two hundred years, and yet they can feel magically modern. 

The primary structure of "Kumano" is a mesh of overlapping angled lines that function just like the hand-printed lines in Kumano-zome textiles.

My background is in abstract painting, and one of my goals for this collection was to create an abstract "painting space" and develop a painterly visual language, and then treat the outputs like I would treat a running series of paintings; exploring and working through all the ideas, within certain constraints, trying to exhaust every possibility.

I wanted the outputs to look like they were created by hand, with soft edges and manual imperfections. Colors are deliberately "mis-registered" and shapes/lines are subtly askew. The "Viscosity" feature turns emergent moir√© patterns into flattened, solid forms, and renders them as if they were painted with watercolors, or stamped with bleeding inks.


The composition of each piece is mostly determined by five main components:

1. Layers of repeating lines at various angles and spacing, which often overlap and interact to create complex moir√© patterns (Kumano Layers)

2. A "Horizon" section that creates a foreground space and a horizon line, bringing the piece into a painterly landscape space

3. Bold caution stripes of various color, thickness, opacity, and orientation

4. Floating "Satellite" shapes that sometimes appear, evoking moons or man-made objects hovering in space

5. A special mix of "Viscosity" and "Erosion" that makes the paint bleed, congeal, and dissolve in unpredictable ways


The overarching color story of each piece is determined by a few interrelated palettes:

- Ten possible Background Colors
- Eight possible palettes for the layered lines (Kumano Palette)
- Eight possible colors of Caution Stripes
- Six possible colors for the Horizon/Foreground layer

When applied in combination and then run through the Viscosity and/or Erosion filters, the breadth of color possibilities is enormous, but always remains connected and coherent.


The algorithm's compositional structure also shows extreme variety, from highly complex to super clean, minimal, and subtle. Everything in the artwork is generated directly from the p5.js script; no external inputs, filters, or images are used.


These pieces are best viewed at large scale in order to appreciate the fine details and nuance. To save a high-res version, just type "S" on your keyboard and a high-res PNG will be generated and downloaded. This can take some time, so please be patient while it renders in the background. In most browsers the high-res output will be 5000 x 6250px (31+ megapixels).

metadata.name: Shift #205
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles ‚Äî dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ‚Äôs‚Äô (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: glory hole$ #673
metadata.description:
our consciousness as humans can be distilled into a crudely fashioned hole at an abandoned dave & busters and the meditative state that is endured while sitting on a neglected toilet praying for the sound of disrupted waters. glory holes embody anonymity and pleasure for pleasure's sake. they are creations that cannot be destroyed, as they exist in the memories of anyone who uses or witnesses. many speculate that the carving of the hole is the purest form of human ingenuity and the desire to explore the unknown. formerly limited to the physical space. these glory holes transcend space and time. and exist in that same unknown that tempts us all. legalize ground beef. create nothing. consume everything.

HUGE thank you to @PureSpider for the layered PNG template, this dream would not have been realized without you friend.

metadata.name: Euphonic #755
metadata.description:
Euphonic is an exploration of the emergent visual properties that arise from placing layers of simple lines atop one another.

In general this effect is called the Moir√© effect. This effect really feels best in the tactile - when you have a printed page and an acetate sheet. This piece attempts to recreate that tactile joy.

This is built in WebGL 2 and so doesn't work in Safari 14 and below. All latest browsers will work as expected.

Licensing: BY-NC-ND see license.md for details.

metadata.name: Precision: angles #128
metadata.description:
This is the first hash-derived entry into my "Precisions" series.  I have been using Precisions as a meditative art practice where I focus on exact positioning of elements, less-emphasized colors, and repetition of geometric shapes.  

In "angles", each element is comprised of right triangles transformed over a common point.  I decided to bring some of the fragmentation from my previous project, "Restrictions", to produce irregular works.  I found beauty in that unpredictable asymmetry and feel it really enhances the structure of this piece.

metadata.name: Interference architecture #94
metadata.description:
In celebration of #fxhashturnsone, this series speaks to the forms that emerge out of interference patterns. The idea was to study the patterns emerging out of parametric equations and how they might interact. For this, first the space is subdivided and a plan is etched out and on top of which some patterns are layered progressively, creating architectures of interference. In a larger context this work aims to reveal emergent aesthetics on interferences of abstract nature.

's' saves the image.
